ation shows good security fundamentals -- `io.LimitReader` on all responses, atomic file writes with correct permissions (0600 file, 0700 directory), strict JSON parsing for the initial handshake, proper context cancellation, and well-isolated integration tests.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: a0fe264a60297b4d2 (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 37611\\ntool_uses: 17\\nduration_ms: 111746</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"0f31cd5f-8e0b-4b13-96a2-da0db2a078ca\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-13T12:37:00.221Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"Perform a security-focused code review of the device auth login feature on the current branch (feat/device-auth-login). The branch adds OAuth 2.0 Device Authorization Grant (RFC 8628) to the CLI.\\n\\nFocus on:\\n1. **Token storage security** - How tokens are stored on disk (file permissions, atomic writes, plaintext vs encrypted)\\n2. **SSRF / URL injection** - The `ENTIRE_API_BASE_URL` env var controls where HTTP requests go; is this validated?\\n3. **Command injection** - The `openBrowser` function passes a URL to shell commands (`open`, `xdg-open`, `cmd /c start`)\\n4. **Credential leakage** - Are tokens logged, printed, or exposed in error messages?\\n5. **Polling loop security** - Is the polling loop bounded? Does it respect `slow_down`? Can the server make the client DoS itself?\\n6. **Response handling** - JSON parsing, response size limits, error handling\\n7. **Race conditions** - The auth file store does read-modify-write; is it safe?\\n8. **TOCTOU in file operations** - Temp file creation and rename\\n\\nKey files to review:\\n- cmd/entire/cli/auth/client.go (HTTP client, device auth flow)\\n- cmd/entire/cli/auth/store.go (token persistence)\\n- cmd/entire/cli/login.go (login command, polling loop, browser opening)\\n- cmd/entire/cli/api/base_url.go (URL resolution)\\n- cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/login_test.go (test coverage)\\n- scripts/local-device-auth-smoke.sh (smoke test script)\\n\\nRead all these files and provide a detailed security assessment with severity ratings (Critical/High/Medium/Low/Info) for each finding.\",\"agentId\":\"a0fe264a60297b4d2\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"The security-focused review has been written to `/Users/dip/Repositories/cli/docs/requirements/device-auth-login/review-01.md`.\\n\\nHere is a summary of the key findings:\\n\\n**Critical (1 finding):**\\n\\n- **Command injection via `openBrowser`** (`login.go:56`) -- The `verification_uri_complete` from the server response is passed directly to OS commands without URL scheme validation. On Windows, `cmd /c start \\\"\\\" <url>` is a shell invocation where metacharacters in the URL can execute arbitrary commands. On all platforms, non-HTTP schemes (`file://`, `smb://`, custom URI handlers) could trigger unintended local actions. Fix: validate that the URL scheme is `https://` (or `http://` only for localhost base URLs) before passing to the browser opener.\\n\\n**Important (4 findings):**\\n\\n- **No scheme validation on `ENTIRE_API_BASE_URL`** (`base_url.go:20-26`) -- The env var accepts any string as a base URL with no scheme check.\\n- **Race condition on auth file read-modify-write** (`store.go:46-61`) -- Concurrent `entire login` from different terminals could lose one token. Low probability but worth documenting or locking.\\n- **Unbounded polling deadline from server** (`login.go:84-86`) -- `expires_in` from the server is trusted without clamping, allowing extremely long or zero-length polling windows.\\n- **No cap on `slow_down` backoff** (`login.go:104-105`) -- Repeated `slow_down` responses grow the interval without limit.\\n\\n**Suggestions (9 findings)** covering response size limit tuning, fsync before rename, ANSI escape sanitization of the user code, and plaintext token storage documentation.\\n\\n**Praise:** The implementation shows good security fundamentals -- `io.LimitReader` on all responses, atomic file writes with correct permissions (0600 file, 0700 directory), strict JSON parsing for the initial handshake, proper context cancellation, and well-isolated integration tests.\"}],\"totalDurationMs\":111746,\"totalTokens\":37611,\"totalToolUseCount\":17,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":2898,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":34231,\"output_tokens\":481,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":2898},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"90a17c71-2987-409c-8986-28ee45bd8a9a\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/dip/Repositories/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"d00e5d15-3b8c-407e-b117-52692226e1d5\",\"version\":\"2.1.74\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"zesty-discovering-rabin\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"0f31cd5f-8e0b-4b13-96a2-da0db2a078ca\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01CoB4szLkkFb8mSSd2T3B2F\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"## Security Review: Device Auth Login (`feat/device-auth-login`)\\n\\n### Critical\\n\\n**1. Command injection via `openBrowser`** — `login.go:79-97`\\n\\nThe `verification_uri_complete` returned by the server is passed directly to OS shell commands. On Windows, `cmd /c start \\\"\\\" <url>` is a shell invocation where metacharacters in the URL can execute arbitrary commands. On all platforms, non-HTTP schemes (`file://`, `smb://`, custom URI handlers) could trigger unintended local actions.\\n\\n**Fix:** Validate the URL scheme is `https://` (or `http://` only when the base URL is localhost) before passing to the browser opener.\\n\\n```go\\nfunc openBrowser(ctx context.Context, browserURL string) error {\\n    u, err := url.Parse(browserURL)\\n    if err != nil || (u.Scheme != \\\"https\\\" && u.Scheme != \\\"http\\\") {\\n        return fmt.Errorf(\\\"refusing to open non-HTTP URL: %s\\\", browserURL)\\n    }\\n    // ...existing platform switch...\\n}\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n### High\\n\\n**2. No scheme validation on `ENTIRE_API_BASE_URL`** — `base_url.go:20-26`\\n\\nThe env var accepts any string (`file://`, `ftp://`, etc.) with no scheme check. This controls where all auth HTTP requests go. Should validate `http://` or `https://` only.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Medium\\n\\n**3. Unbounded polling deadline from server** — `login.go:84-86`\\n\\n`expires_in` from the server response is trusted directly without capping. A malicious or buggy server could set `expires_in: 999999999`, keeping the CLI blocking for ~31 years, or `expires_in: 0`, making the flow fail immediately. Add a reasonable cap (e.g., 15 minutes).\\n\\n**4. No cap on `slow_down` backoff accumulation** — `login.go:104-105`\\n\\nEach `slow_down` response adds 5 seconds to the poll interval with no ceiling. Repeated slow_down responses could push the interval to minutes or hours. Cap at something reasonable (e.g., 30 seconds).\\n\\n**5. Race condition on auth file read-modify-write** — `store.go:46-61`\\n\\n`SaveToken` does Load → modify → save without locking. Two concurrent `entire login` processes could clobber each other's tokens. Low probability in practice, but a file lock would make this robust.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Low / Informational\\n\\n**6. Tokens stored in plaintext** — `store.go`\\n\\nTokens are written as plain JSON to `~/.config/entire/auth.json`. File permissions (0600) are correct, but no OS keychain integration. Acceptable for a CLI tool, but worth documenting in user-facing docs.\\n\\n**7. No `fsync` before rename** — `store.go:108-115`\\n\\nThe atomic write pattern (write to temp → rename) doesn't call `tmpFile.Sync()` before closing. On crash, the renamed file could be empty/truncated on some filesystems. Low risk but easy to add.\\n\\n**8. User code printed without sanitization** — `login.go:45`\\n\\n`start.UserCode` from the server is printed directly. If it contains ANSI escape sequences, it could manipulate terminal output. Very low risk since this comes from the Entire API.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Positive Observations\\n\\n- `io.LimitReader` (1MB cap) on all HTTP responses — prevents memory exhaustion\\n- Atomic file writes with correct permissions (0600 file, 0700 directory)\\n- `DisallowUnknownFields()` on the initial handshake response (strict parsing)\\n- Proper `context.Context` propagation and cancellation support\\n- Well-isolated integration tests with `httptest.NewServer`\\n- `browserOpener` is a package-level var for testability\\n\\nThe most actionable fix is **#1 (command injection)** — add URL scheme validation before passing to the browser opener.\"}],\"stop_reason\":\"end_turn\",\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":1078,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":42487,\"output_tokens\":948,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":1078,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CZ16DJrG3oWtMW94oR1D7\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"f822f759-a2f0-4bfc-821d-cb5d8fb49f80\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-13T12:37:19.190Z\",\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/dip/Repositories/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"d00e5d15-3b8c-407e-b117-52692226e1d5\",\"version\":\"2.1.74\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/device-auth-login\",\"slug\":\"zesty-discovering-rabin\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"f822f759-a2f0-4bfc-821d-cb5d8fb49f80\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"Stop\",\"hookName\":\"Stop\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code stop\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"261be6c5-edd7-48d1-9d81-81ace11de8cf\",\"toolUseID\":\"261be6c5-edd7-48d1-9d81-81ace11de8cf\",\"timesta